myPromise.then((data) => {
  // Handle successful resolution here...
  console.log("Success: ", data);
}).catch((error) => {
  // Handle rejection (failure) here...
  console.log("Error: ", error);
}).finally(() => {
  // This block will always run, regardless of whether the promise resolved or rejected.
  console.log("Finished! ");
});
```

In summary, promises provide a cleaner and more structured way to handle asynchronous operations in JavaScript, allowing us to write more organized and readable code. By following the promise pattern, we can also make our code more testable and easier to reason about.

